Problem 1

The Pharmaceutical Benefit Scheme (PBS) provides a subsidy for many pharmaceutical products sold in Australia, and the expenditure depends on what people purchase during the year.

Consider the PBS data which has aggregation structure ATC1 * Concession * Type.

For simplicity, we will focus on data with ATC1 equal to A (Alimentary tract and metabolism) or B (Blood and blood forming organs).

We will ignore ATC2 to speed up the analysis.

  1. Produce plots of the aggregated data by Concession, Type and ATC1.

  2. Forecast the PBS Scripts data using ETS and SNAIVE models, applied to all but the last three years of data.

  3. Reconcile each of the forecasts using the bottom_up approach.

  4. Which type of model works best on the test set?

  5. Does the reconciliation improve the forecast accuracy?

  6. Why doesnt the reconciliation make any difference to the SNAIVE forecasts?

Problem 1 Solutions

  1. Produce plots of the aggregated data by Concession, Type and ATC1.
# Fill gaps with 0s
PBS_small <- PBS |>
  filter(ATC1 %in% c("A","B")) |>
  fill_gaps(Scripts=0, .full=TRUE)

# Find series that are only 0s and exclude them.
PBS_small_zeros <- PBS_small |>
  as_tibble() |>
  group_by(ATC1, Concession, Type) |>
  summarise(mas = mean(abs(Scripts))) |>
  filter(mas==0)

PBS_small <- PBS_small |>
  anti_join(PBS_small_zeros)

# Aggregate data
PBSagg <- PBS_small |>
  aggregate_key(ATC1 * Concession * Type, Scripts = sum(Scripts))

PBSagg |>
  filter(!is_aggregated(Concession), is_aggregated(Type), is_aggregated(ATC1)) |>
  autoplot(Scripts, aes(color=Concession)) +
  facet_wrap(Concession~., scales="free")

PBSagg |>
  filter(is_aggregated(Concession), !is_aggregated(Type), is_aggregated(ATC1)) |>
  autoplot(Scripts, aes(color=Type)) +
  facet_wrap(Type~., scales="free")

PBSagg |>
  filter(is_aggregated(Concession), is_aggregated(Type), !is_aggregated(ATC1)) |>
  autoplot(Scripts, aes(color=ATC1))

  1. Forecast the PBS Scripts data using ETS, ARIMA and SNAIVE models, applied to all but the last three years of data.
  2. Reconcile each of the forecasts using MinT.
PBSfc <- PBSagg |>
  filter(Month < max(Month)-3*12) |>
  model(
    ets = ETS(Scripts),
    snaive = SNAIVE(Scripts)
  ) |>
  reconcile(
    ets2 = bottom_up(ets),
    snaive2 = bottom_up(snaive)
  ) |>
  forecast(h = "3 years")
  1. Which type of model works best on the test set?
PBSfc |>
  accuracy(PBSagg) |>
  filter(is_aggregated(Concession), is_aggregated(Type), is_aggregated(ATC1)) |>
  select(.model, RMSE, RMSSE)
  1. Does the reconciliation improve the forecast accuracy?

The ETS model shows some improvements after reconciliation.

  1. Why doesnt the reconciliation make any difference to the SNAIVE forecasts?

SNAIVE forecasts are already coherent because they are simply equal to the last year of observed data.
